column62: I came in to submit my order and the system automatically submitted it for me. I do not appreciate this action from Scholastic. I like to submit my own orders because I usually get money to spend for submitted orders. Because Scholastic went ahead and submitted my order, I didn't have this option and missed out and getting free books. I'm very unhappy about this. Also, I do not like that now I do not have the option to choose my Due Date. Now the system automatically chooses a date for me. I've been using this program for many years and this is the first year I have encountered these issues that honestly make me want to get out of the club. It is very unlikely that I will recommend Scholastic Book club to a colleague.

column62: There seem to have been many changes in the books that are offered now. There used to be SO many wonderful books and they had levels which was a great feature for parents who wanted to purchase books at their child's level.  Now it seems like all the junk that comes at the Book Fair at our school (erasers, pens, video game themed books).  Unless I am missing something, I am a little disappointed. I am thinking that it may not even  be worth offering Scholastic Book Clubs to my class this year.  Since COVID, I have barely had parents order at all. If there are not good books at great prices like in the past what is the draw?  It takes a bit of time to pick recommendations, put in any orders, etc. I really do hope that I am missing something and after browsing some more, I will find some more quality books.  After using Scholastic for the last 25 years with my students, I have to say that I am sad about the changes.

column62: I am dissatisfied with the overall selection of books now for my class.  Over the last several years I buy my class books monthly but sincerely cannot afford to do so at $2 plus dollars a book.  I was told the quality of the books was being improved which is the reason for the higher cost, yet the book I just ordered were small and much smaller than books I have received in the past.  I will be looking at other places for a better value for books since I have limited funds to do so each month.  I know I am not the only educator feeling the same way.  Also I am unhappy with the way families are being forced to order online.  Many of my families like to order directly using the book order forms, not online.  Scholastic, I am afraid you will be seeing a huge decrease in teachers utilizing your company now and it is very sad to see this happen.  I hope you do take into consideration feedback that educators are giving currently and you can return some of the promotions you used to do like $

column62: I am so disappointed in the changes Scholastic Book Clubs has made. 1st of all, requiring all families to order online is inequitable. Secondly, your prices have increased greatly, or your selection has changed, making inexpensive choices under $3 minimal at best.  Thirdly, your flyer no longer contains book summaries nor information regarding reading levels, which was always helpful for families of early readers trying to match their child's reading levels and allowed me to stock my own classroom library with books that would help support each of my readers at their own levels.     I have made my purchase today in an effort to use up all of my bonus points, and I have yet to decide if I will even present this new format to my families this year. column62: I have used Book Club every year that I have been in the classroom and I am so sad that these changes make it unusable. I need to set my own due sate to accommodate my school building schedule and my teacher schedule so that shipments can be delivered and I can sort through them for students. I also need to be able to enter student orders for kids who bring me money. With the new changes, there is no way for me to submit student orders. Instead, I will have to come up with a new system in my classroom for how to students order and how I keep track of what is being delivered for them, This puts more work on me - I already don't have the time to do what I need. The changes that Scholastic has made means that my students don't have equitable access to ordering and I have to do more work to make up for Scholastic's oversight and shortcomings. Please change the online due date system and give teachers the ability to enter student orders. Otherwise, I can no longer participate.

column62: Your site is much worse now that the parents have to pay via the internet. Did you ever think about the immigrant families who may not have wifi or don't have credit cards? Many parent deal in cash only transactions in our district. I have parents who have asked me to put in the order for them and they will give me cash. Now, I'm left to pay the tax on the bill because I don't want to ask them for more money, especially since they want books for their kids. You could have left the option up to the parents whether they wanted to order online or with the teacher. So far I have ONE online parent order, when I generally have a $300+ order for September. If the numbers continue to be low, I will discontinue using scholastic and shut my account down after 25 years. I won't be worth the hassle anymore. You could have at least asked the teachers if we wanted it this way. I'm so disappointed in Scholastic.

column62: I am a 1st grade teacher in a Title 1 School. A low income urban community. When I opened up the new Scholastic book order form, I was flabbergasted.  What happened to the very affordable, very reasonably priced books that just about anyone can afford. The new, higher, prices have just completely taken away a great way to get books in the hands of the disadvantaged students. You now just cater to higher income families and districts, it seems.  I'm very disappointed. It's not just me. I belong to several teacher Facebook groups and many of my colleagues in this field agree and we all just tossed the order forms in the trash can because Scholastic Books are no longer affordable to our students.

Perrysburg, OH 43551    Item #42Y1 in 4th & 5th Grade (Back to School)  Grades: 1 - 5  Ages: 6 - 10  Format: Stationery  So cute! But, I have spent the last three years growing "book sponsors" who donate $10 to buy a book a month for a child. I make a big deal, my first graders write a thank you note, and it is a wonderful experience for the kids. Also, I liked the 5 for $5 deals because I sometimes chose that book for a monthly book choice.

column62: I am sad about a lot of the changes in the Book Club.  I have taught at inner city schools for more than 30 years.  Many of my orders in the past have been for the cheapest books, and with cash.  I also would order class sets of the value book to give away each month.  Also, I am sad that the best items from the bonus point catalog are now gone (gift cards, electronics, etc.)   Finally, I feel that it is not ethical for your company to ask for all of the email addresses of the families in my classroom.  That invades their privacy, and I could get in trouble for giving out their private information.

column62: What happened to the even dollar amounts? This makes it difficult to select the $10 free books when it can't add exactly to $10. Teachers originally chose Scholastic because of the low pricing and now it seems that books are going to keep getting more and more expensive. If this is the case I will choose to not send home flyers for students and purchase classroom books elsewhere. I was extremely disappointed when Scholastic removed the dollar book options and made it so that you had to spend a certain amount to access them. Teachers are already giving so much of their own money to schools and classrooms. Overall just very disappointed in this company and how much it has changed over time. It seems as though the reason for changes is to make more money and not to provide affordable books for classrooms and families. It's discouraging as a teacher to potentially lose something that students and families look forward to. But I will not continue to use Scholastic if prices keep going up.

column62: I wish we could sort the books by price.    Also - WHY can't I change the due date?  I don't like that at all!!  I would have had the first order due in September, so having it due in October feels like it will eliminate an entire month's order.    I don't like the new book club flyer at all!!  Every year I have had a couple families who write checks to order books instead of going online to order.  I'm extremely disappointed that there is no longer a paper order form.  That is not very equitable for our families who struggle with poverty or technological access/knowledge.      The book flyers also came to school on September 14th, which was way too late for me to personally show them to families.  I believe that will also cause a drop in sales.    My interest in using Scholastic Book Clubs has gone down this year.

column62: I am really disappointed that Scholastic has changed how students are "supposed" to submit their book orders. Many of my student's families are unable to submit their orders online. Now I will not be earning the monthly rewards unless a family submits an online order. In addition I have to pay the tax for my students since there is no order form on the book order and families are unaware that you now charge tax. I really wish you would not have made these changes. column62: I'm not thrilled with the changes to the system.  I appreciated the flexibility of being able to set my own due date and now they're set.  It also seems like it's going to be much harder to earn bonus points now - especially that old great September incentive.  A teacher at school who was saving points for something specific said the store's been revamped and she was disappointed with the choices.  I hope I get used to the site, but flexibility and bonus points were a huge reason why I use Scholastic Book Clubs.  If I am going to purchase gift books for my kids because either I don't have enough bonus points or because of favorite titles not available any more (How Full is your Bucket for Kids, Kevin Henkes, The Gruffalo, My Father's Dragon, and more) I will spend my money at a local bookstore.  I'm glad you're soliciting input and hope the changes end up being positive.

column62: As a teacher, I am extremely disappointed and frustrated by all the changes to Scholastic Book Clubs this year. All the things I loved have been taken away: no 10,000 bonus points, no MacBooks or gift cards in the bonus catalog, no $1 books, no Golden Apple Teacher benefits, no monthly/themed flyers, no flexible due dates. Despite having a low teacher salary, I have invested hundreds of dollars of my own money on Scholastic orders over the years to earn bonus points so that I could save up toward a MacBook Air. Now Scholastic has taken that away and all that money I spent has been wasted. I keep checking the site, hoping that Scholastic will reinstate these things, but continue to be disappointed and frustrated by Scholastic.

At this time, I would not consider recommending Scholastic Book Clubs to colleagues.

column62: The price of the books has increased so much! I'd like to see some of the lower priced books return to the flyers. Even it was a few every month, that would help.    Bonus Point Catalog--Please bring back some of the higher quality bonus points catalog items, such as the electronics and gift cards. These items are really missed. The new bonus point catalog is very poor when compared to previous years. I wish I would have used my many, many points previously, rather than holding on to them. Many people have been saving their points to use towards the higher end items, and now they are gone. I am very disappointed.     I have placed a monthly order for years. It has been great for the students, but it was also an incentive for me to get the points. Now that those higher end items are not offered, I don't know that I will go through the hassle of managing monthly book orders. It may not be worth my time. Please consider bringing them back.

column62: I have been a teacher for 10 years and have been a member of Scholastic Book Clubs since I began. For the last 5 years, I have fundraised to be able to provide my students with a book every month  and birthday coupons. I have raised thousands of dollars to be able to put books into my students hands and I have spent all of that money with you. This year, I raised what should be more than enough money to provide my students with books, but I cannot afford to purchase more than 4 books for each student this year. I understand that inflation is unavoidable, but the prices have skyrocketed. There are no longer dollar books, the dollar book bonus store, birthday coupons, nor are there quality value packs for a reasonable price. The $2 book of the month has also been the same for the last 6 weeks. Again, I understand that a price hike was necessary, but this increase has made it impossible to gift books to our students and will force me to look elsewhere.

column62: I will not be entering email addresses for my families into your site.  I believe that sharing this kind of personal information without the knowledge of the family is bad practice.  If parents choose to sign up and order books, that is their choice.  My parents are concerned about who has their information and asking permission makes more work for me.  I use my physical flyers as part of my class "homework." I ask parents to sit with their children and look through the flyer and look for books their child is excited about.  They can choose to order from Scholastic or look for them at the library.  I believe they physical flyers are an important part of the process.  They foster parent/child interactions as they sit and look at the flyer together, they help the parent better understand the interests of their child, and they help children understand the concept of ordering something from a physical catalog not just from a screen.

column62: I was surprised to see the limited number of selections available in the first Scholastic flyer!  I was hoping to see more timeless literature titles and authors.  Where are the award winners, both new and old?  Children may choose pop culture titles, but parents are going to actually purchase books that they remember reading as children.  They will be more likely to buy a book that they remember as being a great story or one that someone special to them read to them as a child than a title they know nothing about.  I am having a harder and harder time selling the idea that parents can purchase high quality children's literature from Scholastic. I have been a Golden Apple teacher for many years, and I am not sure how much longer I will continue.

column62: I would like to offer my insights as a long time Golden Apple classroom teacher on the roll out of the new Scholastic book clubs site.  I was very disappointed with the way the new changes were rolled out.  I discovered the changes simply by trying to change the due date of my "September" class order.  When I discovered that I could not change the due date of my order, I had to go looking for the rest of the new changes.  I had already printed my letter to the parents which will now have to be wastefully discarded.  A more prominent letter or email notification that this kind of change was being made would have been appreciated.  The start of school is hard enough without having to make changes to routine and regular systems without warning.  I did consider just trying to spend my 120K+ bonus points and throwing the flyers away.

column62: Disappointed that I couldn't find the Student Birthday Coupons. Also, what happened to Judy Newman's Dollar Deals? I couldn't even search for books in the $1-$2  range, it was all grouped together in the $5-6 category. Super unhelpful. A lot of the recent changes seems "marketed" as making it "easier" on us teachers, but really the changes come across as Scholastic being cheap (less printed flyers, and less often, to save printing costs higher book prices fewer products no support for cash orders fewer rewards etc). I know there was a change in leadership recently, but come on, you're gutting one of the best programs for getting books into the hands of students and teachers. I don't think there is a single change that has been made this year that I actually find helpful.

column62: Scholastic Book Clubs used to send books to my home address, even BEFORE THE PANDEMIC, because I teach virtually for a virtual school. Now Scholastic refuses to recognize that virtual education teachers WORK FROM HOME and send the books to OUR HOMES so that WE CAN SEND THEM TO STUDENTS! FIX IT! I will NOT SPEND A SINGLE PENNY UNTIL BOOKS ARE SHIPPED DIRECTLY TO ME AT MY HOME!!!!!!! I have had that on my account since 2017! Now, suddenly, you want to say it isn't an option? Customer support won't even listen long enough to know that shipping to the school's "address" IS NOT AN OPTION. No, I WILL NOT use the Scholastic store. The ONLY reason I buy from Scholastic is the Bonus Points. I AM A FREAKING GOLD APPLE TEACHER!!!!

column62: I have been a teaching for 15 years and have always LOVED offering Scholastic books clubs for my student to order.  I even have gotten my students sponsored each year so that EVERY student gets a book with each monthly order.  I am about to place my order for the first time this year and to say I am disappointed with the prices and selection options is a vast understatment.  I understand that prices have gone up but when the cheapest book in a book order is 4.99 you are elimanting the affordability that has so often spearheaded orders.  I used to also get 2-3 different types of flyers to send home and each flyer had at least 4 pages of books to look through...now we get 1 flyer and it is single paged.      The cost to teachers is great in many areas but you have now made it to so that the inspiring students to read comes 100% down to money.  That is incredibly sad and disappointing.      I don't know what the fix is but this is NOT the Scholastic I have come to expect!!!

column62: Man oh man...there are many disappointments with Scholastic!     Why are the prices so dang high?  And the excuse of "higher quality books" doesn't shake it when people are priced out of buying books!!!      I myself am using other sources to buy books for myself and for my scholars. I have my friends and family donate monies to my class so they have a free book to take home each month. I cannot use this resource to buy those books because they are too far overpriced.    Where are the Dollar Books?  Where is the opportunity to  go to the Teachers Dollar Store to get even MORE books for our scholars?    Isn't the goal to get quality book titles into the scholars' hands  so they can READ??????    My rating to recommend Scholastic to a colleague is MUCH lower because of the concerns I have scribed above.  The site is not catering to the scholars and their families!!!      ***************************************************************************************************    On a TEACHERS'

column46: Other, To find out why the flyers are different this year and see why you decided to make buying books inaccessible to my students
column62: Just curious. but why are the flyers different this year and the prices changed? I work with a lot of low income families in a school with a high percentage of English Learners. The flyers now will not work with my families and I will probably never get any orders. My students used to love getting the flyers since they could manage to try and find a dollar or two and be able to buy a book. Usually their parents wouldn't give them money for the order. I used to love that Scholastic made buying books accessible to all children, but this is awful. I am an EL teacher and most of my families speak Spanish. My families will not order books online. They never have and I can guarantee that never will. My students used to try and find money however they could to get something out of the order and their excitement was infectious. Thank you for ruining the joy that a book box could bring.
